Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment: Coming back to this after a while, it's nice seeing the e3 trailer actual showed a game almost complete, they were probably just working on story stuff and getting all the ruins and cities and all that in, seems like the core game mechanics were already in though, movement seems almost if not completely identical, stealth is right up in there, so core gameplay looks like it stayed faithful since, UI improved imo, but that's subjective, kinda in the fence about the watcher alert sound, the current one sounds more animalistic and natural, and when taking the lore into consideration, makes more sense, but something about this one gets your adrenaline pumping right away, something the one now loses quick, and obviously you'd get used to this one too, but probably much later on, only criticism I have is no more roaming tallnecks, ik its not important, but come one, who wouldn't appreciate some roaming tallneck hoards every once in a while, but that's just a lil preference thing, so not even a critique, just wanted to appreciate this e3, no graphics downgrade, showed off a truly work in progress game, you could see that true work was done, it doesn't feel so different from the game we have now, which feels even better, just a few noticable changes and that's it, and that's what I'd expect two years after e3, not the whole game being thrown away, seems to be the normal case nowadays, hzd should be the norm, at e3 we should see games with work done but more to be done, don't need to see a full polished game at e3, but show us that work is being done, and release the game and show us that you built beyond what we were already shown, don't show us a cool concept and cool looking game, then release in a WORSE state

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
That city at 0:58 was it meant to be shown to us? but we just never got to see it? I‚Äôve finished the game twice now and nothing like that ever popped up, too bad really, as I delved deeper into the story there was so much I wanted to know including what the old world looked like, if this is truly a picture of it then at least I didn‚Äôt cry for no reason. 

There was also something else I never saw, the water pouring out of the buildings, been to that area like a crazy amount of times and have never seen that. 

I hope the sequel has a go back to the old world moment, there is so much I think about when I think about the game, I cry every time I think about it too, the story and the greed of Ted freaking Faro that ended the world with his war robot BS lol, get so angry thinking about what he did. I guess it‚Äôs great that the world got to live on, but his messing with Apollo meant that stupid things like killing people to appease the machines happened and other horrific unnecessary things. I hope we also get to repair Gaia somehow, after all until she‚Äôs back in control the world will only get worse, the more dangerous machines that get built the worse off the people will be, eventually unable to fight them off. A pop in to enduring victory would be nice also, I want to see what the world was like when they were attacking. Few other things too.

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment: I have grown to absolutely love this game. Having just finished Witcher 3 and its expansion packs, understandably I was a bit depressed after that memorable gaming experience. It took me a little while to get used to the gaming mechanics, but once I started getting better modifications and items, the story and gameplay drew me in and made me forget about Witcher 3. That to me is the highest compliment. Horizon Dawn borrows elements and mechanics from many other games, but somehow manages to make it its own in a very special way.

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
After playing the final release, I wanted to see what changed between this and the end game. Of course the voice acting and encounter was scripted just for the trailer, but similar style of dialogue occurs in quests, as well as commentary by the Play character on the current situation and while exploring, so that doesn't disappoint. 

Combat is the same, as well as the environment. Only real disappointment is that the giant robots, the Tallnecks (giraffes) and the Thunderjaws (T-rexs) don't move freely in the world, or in pairs. The Tallnecks are restricted to moving in a set pattern around in circles, and are few and far between.

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment: I feel like this game is what Zoids would be if the whole "Fully functioning and thinking robot animals" were all wild and humanity collapsed.  For the people wondering why she was hunting them, I think her talking about the canisters on their backs indicates that they do have something on them that makes them worth hunting.  Probably some kind of power supply for what little tech they still have.  Maybe they refine nutrients from plants and they drink the stuff or something, who knows?  I do agree with the folks who thought that other robot should have been able to spot her in the bushes if it had any kind of higher optical functions than normal animals, but maybe for whatever reason it doesn't, or dismissed her as something else.  I'm looking forward to seeing how this game does things, though.  If nothing else, it looks interesting enough.  Kind of like a Tomb Raider meets Monster Hunter type deal with giant robots thrown in.

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
Visuals were nice but I can tell they've got a lot of work ahead of them, before they release.
Dialogue doesn't match the face, maybe a little bit too much talking, and sympathy for a robot? What? Maybe that will be explained later but the question that is nagging me the most: How come they're choosing to live as natives, yet there were cities that could have been salvaged? I'm sure this will be answered as well but.. how do they have technologically advanced weapons but live in shacks? That, I don't get.. and I'm not even sure if the story is developed enough to explain it either.

I'll be honest, this game could be amazing but I just have this feeling like it won't go much further than what we see here.

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
I'll sell my soul for this game. What an absolutely masterpiece from the looks of it. I've always been fascinated by the subject of a high tech civilization that surpassed ours with science and technology, and might have likely had something to do with our creation or evolution, but something happened and they long perished, leaving no sign of their empire. It's one of the main reasons why I love Assassin's Creed.


The fact that we are this high tech, and ancient civilization and the game is set in the distant future makes it even more epic. I was considering this possibility as a twist in the ending or something while watching the trailer, but then I read the official website, and it is actually set in the future

This game, if, as I hope, will focus on this subject, and be highly story driven, more than just being a mechanical dinosaur hunter, will totally be epic and definitely my type of game.

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
Looking from 2:37-2:41 you can see some very ugly popping in the right upper corner of the distant trees. It seems also to be some kind of lighting calculation mistake as there are some more in 5:37-5:39. More popping from 3:10-3:18 , some even pretty close by for textures. Makes me wonder why the fog. Clever way to hide the problems? - That would be a good way to do it if it fits the atmosphere.

Still, I'm impressed by the quality, but just wondering if the 550k poly Thunderjaw is worth the strain it puts on the PS4. You clearly have to make some trade-offs.

Personally I don't care for extremely detailed models if it means visible popping. I would much rather have less details overall on models (with great textures) and use the free performance for better FOV.

Comment:
I have a theory as to why there are mechanical wildlife and why the "humans before" are gone:¬†
Human influence nearly brought all the original animals to extinction, so they found a way to use machines as a means of not only repopulating the Earth with wildlife (but to also use them as natural resources or a means to gain those resources, like those mechanical deer with those tubes on their backs).¬†

Think of the "Salient Green" from Fallout New Vegas, where you convert all types of plant matter into a simple base substance that can be made into other types of food... I think those mechadeer use those tubes for that purpose.

However, a few other creations led to the loss of common electrical power, which made most humans lose their homes and a means to make a living, while also likely being attacked and killed by the creations.¬†

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
Really stunning! These landscapes are evocative and vibrant, and it's really cool that they're contrasting the organic scenery with very inorganic creatures, rather than the other way around, as is the norm in dystopian storylines.

I'm kinda curious, though, how the change in landscape is so great after only about 1,000 years; I'd assume it would realistically take a whole lot longer for the biodiversity to reestablish and the pollution and excess chemicals and radiation left behind to dissipate. No complaints, of course! Just a thought. ^_^

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment: I freakin LOOOOOOOVE world settings like this. They aren't too common, where you live in an old, early hunter gatherer society (or society scrapping off of whatever left behind) world, where the "ancients" did something and left many things (ancients nothing more than just technologically developed people). Over time, the ancient's remnants develop into variety of creatures, creating a brand new echosystem. Loved Panzer Dragoon (highly inspired by Nausica), Enslaved, etc. I think Enslaved did a great job of this. Unfortunately, not many of these types of games really took it to another level in terms of gameplay imo. Usually what gets me through games is the settings itself. This is looking fantastic though.

Title: Horizon Zero Dawn - E3 2015 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
Today we saw the stunning reveal¬†of Guerrilla Games‚Äô new IP¬†Horizon: Zero Dawn, and today¬†Managing Director Hermen Hulst and Game Director Mathijs de Jonge talked more in depth about the game during¬†a livestream¬†from E3.

Here are a few interesting points they made:

‚ñ´Guerrilla Games worked on the game for four and a half year. After¬†Killzone 3¬†twenty developers starting to work on it. They created concepts and prototypes. After¬†Shadow Fallwas shipped, the ‚Äúbig team‚Äù joined, and after a year and a half they are at the stage we saw yesterday.

‚ñ´This is ‚Äúby far‚Äù the biggest game Guerrilla has ever made.The game is set a thousand years after the apocalypse.

‚ñ´Eloy, the main character is a machine hunter, she‚Äôs about twenty year-old and she‚Äôs one of the best hunters of her tribe.

‚ñ´There‚Äôs a lot of strategy involved in finding out how to defeat the machines.

‚ñ´Defeating the machines lets you gather resources to craft new weapons, ammo and tools.

‚ñ´The game is a seamless open world, there are a large variety of machines, from small like the Watchers to enormous like the Longnecks.

‚ñ´The demo is running on PS4, and is pre-alpha.

‚ñ´Guerrilla games always tries to make benchmark games for visuals on PlayStation platforms, but they don‚Äôt want to go backwards just because it‚Äôs open world, they want to improve graphics. A game like this is much tougher in memory and GPU, so they have been pushing the technical artists to the max.

‚ñ´Having made an engine for¬†Killzone: Shadow Fallwas good for this game too. Prototypes used even Killzone 3 assets. After shipping¬†Shadow Fall, the studio had its own PS4 engine, and a very mature one at that, but then had to implement streaming, and it took a lot of effort to set that up properly, especially with this amount of detail and content. Yet, now the game is running, and the studio wants to build it further up.

‚ñ´The game‚Äôs RPG elements include hunting the machines for resources (beginning with smaller ones to then be able to fighting bigger ones). Crafting is a key component of the game. The game has also ‚Äúa lot‚Äù of quests.

‚ñ´The game is ‚Äúa new horizon‚Äù for Guerrilla Games, and they hope to build it in ‚Äúa fantastic franchise.‚Äù What we‚Äôre seeing now is just the tip of the iceberg. There‚Äôs ‚Äúso much more stuff‚Äù Guerrilla is going to reveal in time, and they‚Äôre really looking forward to show more.
